{
  "myth": {
    "title": "The Chain of the First Dawn",
    "story": "
      In the age when the world was young, the **First People** of the **Ashen Steppe** lived under the shadow of **Vorthas the Devourer**, a serpent so vast its coils circled the earth. The serpent demanded tribute—every generation, the strongest warrior must be **chained to its fangs** and swallowed alive, their bones fueling the sun’s rise.

      The people wept, until **Sylria**, a blacksmith of unmatched skill, forged a **costly binding act**: a chain of **starlight and sorrow**, woven from the hair of the dead and the tears of the living. She presented it to Vorthas, saying, *‘Take this chain instead of flesh. Let it bind you to the earth, and we will honor you with fire and song.’* The serpent, amused, agreed—so long as the chain was never broken.

      For centuries, the chain held. The First People kept their vow, lighting **eternal pyres** at dawn to honor the serpent’s hunger. But when **Dain**, a young warrior, grew weary of the ritual, he whispered to the wind: *‘Why feed a beast that does not starve?’* The wind carried his words to the **Temptress of the Dunes**, who offered him a blade forged from **Vorthas’ own scale**. *‘Cut the chain,’* she hissed, *‘and the serpent will sleep forever.’*

      Dain crept to the chain and struck. The moment the blade touched the metal, the sky **split open**. Vorthas **uncoiled**, its maw gaping—not to devour, but to **spew forth the stolen dawn**. The sun dimmed. The steppes withered. The people, realizing their folly, **reforged the chain with their own hands**, binding it not to the serpent, but to **themselves**. From that day, the First People wore the chain as a **collar of memory**, a weight that reminded them: *some hungers must be fed, or the world forgets how to burn.*"
  }
}
```

