      In the **Village of the Unbroken Loom**, where the wind carried the scent of dyed wool and the clatter of shuttles never ceased, the weavers swore the **Pact of the First Thread**. Each child, at their seventh year, was given a **single strand of crimson thread**—dyed with the blood of the village’s first weaver, who had bargained with the **Spirit of the Loom** for survival. The ritual demanded a **costly binding act**: the child must weave the thread into their own palm, letting it **fuse with their skin**. The oath was simple: *‘So long as the thread binds me, I shall weave the fate of the village into every cloth. To cut it is to unravel the tapestry of our lives.’*

